Written evidence submitted by [bold]Teeside UniversityTeeside University (FSS044)[bold]1. Does the Government have an effective strategy for forensic science in the UK and is it sufficient to support forensic science R&amp;D and criminal justice?
[normal]1.1 
[normal]I
[normal]t 
[normal]doesn’t seem that there is one so the short answer is no.
[normal]1.2 
[normal]There does not appear to be 
[normal]single accepted and coordinated 
[normal]nationwide strategy
[normal] for forensic science practice
[normal]. Individual
[normal] police forces, 
[normal]collaborating police forces
[normal] and the commercial companies may well have 
[normal]their own 
[normal]strategies
[normal] which will almost certainly 
[normal]be different from each other.  For 
[normal]example some police forces are 
[normal]creating t
[normal]heir own forensic lab
[normal]oratories 
[normal]and are doing this 
[normal]with the 
[normal]minimal
[normal] of support and guidance.  A ‘free’ meeting with UKAS may support accreditation but it doesn’t act as a substitute for the force or company strategy 
[normal]to fit UK forensic science
[normal] practice. Th
[normal]e situation is m
[normal]ore complicated with the commercial 
[normal]providers
[normal], many of whom have extensive experience with accreditation but have the additional driver of 
[normal]profit.
[normal]1.3 Unfortunately w
[normal]hat needs to be 
[normal]acknowledged 
[normal]is that the UK reputation in foren
[normal]sic science, built up over many decades is now under threat and needs considerable 
[normal]investment
[normal], innovation and integration within the investigative process to benefit the justice system
[normal] to provide it with assurance and confidence
[normal].
[normal]1.4 
[normal]Glimmers of hope 
[normal]have e
[normal]merg
[normal]ed since the closure of the FSS. 
[normal]1.4.1 
[normal]I
[normal]n
[normal] the area of 
[normal]education
