[normal]2. Did the FSS transition and closure run smoothly and within budget?
[normal]2.1 
[normal]We don’t have sufficient information to comment on this question.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3. What impacts have the FSS’s closure had on (i) the criminal justice system and (ii) forensic science R&amp;D and training? In particular, have the appropriate quality standards and accreditation been rigorously maintained? (please provide evidence/examples)
[normal]3.1 
[normal]Impact on the Criminal Justice System – this is best answered by the 
[normal]judiciary
[normal] in terms of quality and quantity of cases being presented to the CPS and courts.
[normal] However we have seen a 
[normal]recent 
[normal]DNA issue within one of the commercial providers which impacted the justice system. 
[normal]Therefore 
[normal]the bigger question
[normal] which 
[normal]needs to be answered 
[normal]is whether the 
[normal]justice system and public 
[normal]are 
[normal]confiden
[normal]t 
[normal]and 
[normal]assured
[normal] 
[normal]that the development of the industry is supporting public safety while it becomes more 
[normal]fragmented.  
[normal]3.1.1 Further, 
[normal]as more work moves into police forces can we be confident that complaints and issues relating to the provision of scientific evidence be thoroughly and openly managed and resolved. In the light of the 
[normal]Hillsborough
[normal] incident and the Mitchell incident can the public be confident that their forensic provision will remain independent with the highest int
[normal]egrity
[normal]?
[normal] Under the ISO standard all complaints are expected to be logged and covered for independence, impartiality and integrity. 
[normal]3.2 
[normal]The R&amp;D – The FSS 
[normal]intimated
[normal] that they did a lot of research but in the later years before it closed it was questionable if they were still leading 
[normal]the UK 
[normal]in R&amp;D. Although there have been a number of significant changes for the good with 
[normal]the 
[normal]R&amp;D
[normal] review
[normal] (mentioned above) there is still no 
[normal]national 
[normal]coordinated lead 
[normal]or 
[normal]strategy for R&amp;D. 
[normal]3.3 
[normal]The FSS didn't really govern quality in forensic research, but the perception now is that research has been left to fend for itself with limited governmental input.
[normal] 
[normal]3.4 
[normal]There 
[normal]must 
[normal]be a coordinated 
[normal]approach 
[normal]on R&amp;D
[normal] in the UK
[normal].  There is lots being done such as the Forensic Science Society Forum for Universities and Industry, conferences (one day in Nov. 2013 and three days in Nov 2013) but there are still untapped R&amp;D 
[normal]within 
[normal]good quality BSc and MSc level 
[normal]projects. These 
[normal]selected projects could be made available to the community in the same way as PhD’s are.
[normal]3.5 
[normal]Part of the solution must be to 
[normal]enable
[normal] more collaborative partnerships.  The days when there could be one 
[normal]physical 
[normal]central
[normal] research establishment may have passed but the strategic leadership and central coordination is still needed.
[normal] Universities are keen to collaborate with practitioners in police forces and with companies but this still needs national and regional coordination.
[normal] It is without doubt a good thing for police forces and companies to work with 
[normal]Universities such
[normal] as educational awards which Teesside University is involved with but also 
[normal]on
[normal] various other activities including
[normal] 
[normal]research 
[normal]projects. It is quite possible to keep things confidential and the 
[normal]research 
[normal]findings can feed into the bigger picture and guide future good practice. Universities can and would be willing to work 
[normal]confidentially with police forces 
[normal]and companies 
[normal]and only publish their data with permission 
[normal]especially when 
[normal]the findings could have much wider relevance and impact.
[normal]3.6 
[normal]Training – the overall training and continual professional development including continual professional competency is a big area and there have been a number of 
[normal]new 
[normal]SME’s starting to come to market
[normal] since the 
[normal]closure
[normal] of the FSS
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]We 
[normal]would suggest that consistent accreditation and individual competency coupled with the strive for optimisation of practices and procedures 
[normal]within R&amp;D 
[normal]are the biggest areas to provide the justice system with assurance and confidence. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4. What should be role of the Forensic Science Regulator?
[normal]4.1 
[normal]The requirement for and role of the Forensic Science Regulator was clear in 2007/8. However
[normal],
[normal] there are 
[normal]a number of key 
[normal]areas needing addressed. Firstly the 
[normal]statutory
[normal] position 
[normal]of the Regulator 
[normal]and 
[normal]associated 
[normal]powers
[normal] to oversee forensic 
[normal]science 
[normal]practi
[normal]ce. Secondly concerning the area of the practitioner being 
[normal]‘fit to practice’
[normal], possibly linking with the 
[normal]professional body
[normal]. Anyone providing evidence to court needs to be fit to practice. Thirdly 
[normal]it needs to be recognised that the 
[normal]Regulator 
[normal]is not the 
[normal]person 
[normal]to throw all the forensic science 
[normal]practice 
[normal]issues at such as 
[normal]funding, 
[normal]CCTV and research.
[normal] 
[normal]4.2 
[normal]There is a need to ring fence the role within the quality arena – set, maintain and 
[normal]monitor
[normal] and then identify the other areas with overlap but outside the remit of the 
[normal]R
[normal]egulator. For 
[normal]example
[normal] does research fit comfortably with the 
[normal]R
[normal]egulator or can the 
[normal]R
[normal]egulator be the conduit to 
[normal]coordinating research with practice.
[normal]4.3 
[normal]We should not believe that accreditation to the ISO standards such as 17025 and 17020 will ensure consistency of quality standards or enable continual improvement to provide best evidence to the courts.
[normal]4.4 
[normal]The Police are in a difficult situation with their budgets and the greater provision on in-house forensic practice. They also need to contribute to the improvement in quality standards and carry out research.  As a minimum they need to set up partnerships with commercial companies and Universities to enable worthwhile R&amp;D.
[normal]5. What is the size of the forensics market and how stable is it?
[normal]5.1 
[normal]This is a difficult question 
[normal]because
[normal] one needs to define the ‘forensics market’.  For example when the Home Office were considering the 
[normal]size
[normal] of the market during the transition of the FSS to a GovCo the 
[normal]market
[normal] was estimated at 
[normal]a
[normal]n
[normal] amount considerably more than that now being suggested
[normal] – less than £100m. It is important to be able estimate the size of the total market and not just the commercial company slice.
[normal] 
[normal]5.
[normal]2
[normal] 
[normal]Nevertheless the market size seems to be 
[normal]judged
[normal] by the amount the commercial sector is involved with – currently about £80m and 
[normal]therefore
[normal] falling.  The overall size including all the police forces, commercial providers, Universities / SME 
[normal]etc.
[normal] 
[normal]is probably 
[normal]fairly
[normal] stable.  The full question 
[normal]can’t
[normal] be answered until the police forces understand what their forensic provision costs using the same model as the commercial providers and include not only the building and over heads but HR, finance etc.
[normal] 
[normal]5.
[normal]3
[normal] 
[normal]Overall our 
[normal]feeling may well be that the market is growing due to 
[normal]its 
[normal]fragmentation
[normal].  The size of the market should be confused with the quality of the 
[normal]service to the justice system.
[normal]6. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]How are forensic science services procured by police forces and could procurement processes be improved?
[normal]6.1 
[normal]We have insufficient intimate knowledge of the procurement process. However, anecdotal evidence would suggest that there is a large 
[normal]bureaucratic
[normal] beast dealing with this (which should be part of the calculation on the 
[normal]size
[normal] of the market and drain on police budgets).  Small companies seem to spend an enormous amount of time filling out forms to apply within the procurement process.
[normal]6.2 
[normal]One could argue that there is no need for such a process and let the customers purchase, under guidelines, the service they require. The key difficulty here is the phrase ‘level the playing field’ and the transparency of procurement process.
[normal]7. Has the closure of the FSS resulted in a loss of intellectual wealth through its scientists leaving the forensic science profession, or the UK? (please provide evidence/examples)
[normal].
[normal]7.1 
[normal]Yes, 
[normal]from one x FSS 
[normal]employee 
[normal]–
[normal] 
[normal]“
[normal]only half of the people I worked with now have jobs within the industry - they are deemed too expensive possibly when graduates can be used for a low cost. Examples of where they have ended up: dentists 
[normal]assistant
[normal], moved to Canada, working for environment agency, unemployed (returning to education) 
[normal]etc.
[normal]”
[normal]8. Are current arrangements for the FSS’s archives satisfactory? How could arrangements for the retention of case files and forensic materials in the UK be improved?
[normal]We consider that the question is much bigger than only the FSS archive.  It should relate to the case files and associated materials for all police forces, commercia
[normal]l providers and other providers, including the process to deal with the retention and storage of materials if a police force or company no longer undertakes forensic science practice.
[normal] The time scales are clear for retention but 
[normal]the actual physical retention across the UK is key
[normal] to support the justice system
[normal].
